          "body": "The superscription names the psalm *mizmor letodah* — a psalm for the thank-offering. *Todah* in Leviticus 7:12-15 is a specific subset of the peace-offering, brought in response to deliverance, eaten the same day in fellowship with God and community. The psalm was sung by pilgrims processing into the temple with their *todah* sacrifice. By verse 4 the word reappears: *enter His gates with todah*. Now it refers simultaneously to the offering being brought and the inward disposition of the worshiper. Sacrifice and gratitude are inseparable. The New Testament gathers this trajectory into Hebrews 13:15 — *through Him then let us continually offer up a sacrifice of praise to God, that is, the fruit of lips that give thanks to His name*. The Christian's ongoing *todah* is the worship of grateful lips, made possible by the one final sacrifice of the Lamb."
