        "title": "The universal summons — all the earth before the King",
        "range": "100:1-2",
        "excerpt": "Shout joyfully to the LORD, all the earth. Serve the LORD with gladness; come before Him with joyful singing.",
        "body": "The psalm opens with the loudest sound in the Hebrew Bible's worship vocabulary. *Shout joyfully* (*hari'u*) is the verb used when Israel's army acclaimed Saul as king (1 Samuel 10:24), when the walls of Jericho fell (Joshua 6:5), and when the foundation of the second temple was laid (Ezra 3:11). It is the ear-piercing roar of a people receiving its king. The first word of the psalm thus signals what is happening: YHWH is being acclaimed as King, and the acclamation is being demanded of *all the earth*.\n\nThe scope refuses any narrowing. *Kol-ha'arets* — every land, every nation. This is the climactic invitation of the enthronement collection. Psalms 93-99 have built the theological case that YHWH reigns over the whole earth; Psalm 100 issues the corresponding summons. Every nation is now commanded to render the acclamation that the LORD's universal kingship requires. The psalm anticipates Isaiah 2:2-4, Zechariah 14:16, and ultimately Revelation 7:9-10, where the multitude from every nation stands before the throne and the Lamb.\n\nVerse 2 specifies the manner: *serve the LORD with gladness*. The verb *avad* covers both worship and labor — the same root that names Israel's slavery in Egypt now names her free service to YHWH. The qualifier matters more than English readers typically notice. *With gladness* (*be'simchah*) excludes grudging, dutiful, joyless service from the category of legitimate worship. A scowling worshiper is not merely a weak worshiper; he is rendering service in a manner the psalm's grammar forbids. Calvin's comment is sharp: *God is not pleased with any service which is not voluntary and cheerfully rendered*.\n\nThe second half of verse 2 — *come before Him with joyful singing* — names the destination and the soundtrack of the approach. *His presence* is literally *His face* (*panav*) — the symbolic place where the worshiper meets God directly. The accompanying *renanah* is the ringing, exuberant song that breaks out aloud. Approach to God is loud. It is glad. It is sung. The picture is a procession of nations streaming toward His face with vocal joy — and the psalmist commands this on every nation's behalf.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hari'u* (shout joyfully) from *rua* — the war-cry, coronation-acclamation verb. *Avad* — the verb of cultic service and ordinary labor; context here is unambiguously cultic. *Simchah* — festival rejoicing (Deuteronomy 16:14-15). *Panav* (His presence) — literally *His face*. *Renanah* — ringing musical cry, vocalized joy."
